# App Proxy UI Patterns

The app proxy dashboard is served through Shopify's storefront servers.
React client-side hydration does NOT activate in this context.

## What does NOT work

- `useState` — state changes are silently ignored, UI never updates
- `onClick` handlers on buttons — no effect
- `useEffect`, `useNavigation`, `useTransition` — not running

## What DOES work

- Server-rendered HTML (initial render only)
- Plain `<a href>` links — full page navigations
- `<Form method="post" action={baseUrl}>` from react-router — **must include explicit `action`**
- `redirect()` returned from the action — browser follows it

## CRITICAL: Always set an explicit `action` on `<Form>`

Without an explicit `action`, React Router SSR renders the form with the **app server URL**
(`railway.app/...`) as the action. The browser POSTs directly to the app server, bypassing
Shopify's proxy. `authenticate.public.appProxy` gets a request with no valid HMAC → 400 Bad Request.

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG — no action, React Router SSR defaults to app server URL → Bad Request
<Form method="post">

// ✅ CORRECT — explicit Shopify storefront URL goes through the App Proxy
<Form method="post" action={baseUrl}>
```

`baseUrl` is the Shopify storefront URL (e.g. `https://my-shop.myshopify.com/apps/rt-auth/dashboard`).
It is constructed in the loader from `shop` + `path_prefix` query params and passed down as a prop.

## Pattern: URL-driven state

Use query params instead of `useState`. Read them in the loader, pass as props.

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG — onClick and useState are dead
const [showForm, setShowForm] = useState(false);
<button onClick={() => setShowForm(true)}>Legg til</button>
{showForm ? <Form /> : null}

// ✅ CORRECT — URL-driven, works without JS
// In loader: const formMode = url.searchParams.get("form");
// Passed as prop: formMode === "create"
<a href={`${baseUrl}?tab=adresser&form=create`}>Legg til</a>
{formMode === "create" ? <Form cancelHref={`${baseUrl}?tab=adresser`} /> : null}
```

## Pattern: Action redirect after mutation

Return `redirect()` from the action — never `Response.json({ ok: true })` alone.
The redirect clears the form state from the URL and reloads the page with fresh loader data.

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG — browser displays raw JSON
return Response.json({ ok: true });

// ✅ CORRECT — browser navigates back, form disappears, data reloads
const redirectUrl = new URL(url.toString());
redirectUrl.searchParams.delete("form");
redirectUrl.searchParams.delete("addressId");
return redirect(redirectUrl.toString());
```

## Pattern: Navigation links instead of onClick

Use `actionHref` on `DataTable` (renders `<a>`) instead of `onActionClick` (requires JS).
For per-row actions, add a column with `render: (row) => <a href={...}>` instead of `rowAction.onClick`.

